 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Cerilius</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Cerilius, I'd like to draw your attention to a few different spells here.  The first one is called Manaskin.  Not quite as good as Rune V, but two can play that game eh?<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>That's true, but keep in mind that Manaskin takes 330 mana to refresh. Near the end of the fight, when your mana bar is completely empty, staying alive isn't as easy as chain-buffing yourself.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Secondly, assuming he prepared his buff list properly, throw in a quick siphon strength, and then dot the fuck out of him.  You fill up his #1 buff slot and suddenly he has to dispell his own buffs just to get at your dot.  You can have him re-pyroed/re siphoned in the time it takes annul magic to repop.  If he was smart enough to leave 2 slots empty...no problem, use ShadowVortex too.  Pyro/Pyre+Splurt are more than enough to finish him rune and all.  While he frantically dispells himself, you Touch of Night. End of Enchanter.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>The debuff tactic, while very useful, has several limitations (which I trust nobody will disclose outside this forum <img src=icon_smile_wink.gif border=0 align=middle>):</P><P>1) If the enchanter is properly buffed and knows what he's doing, he'll click off his second trash buff immediately after being siphoned, leaving room for Pyro/Splurt. This means Shadow Vortex *must* be used -- Siphon Strength alone won't do. </P><P>2) If he sees you casting Shadow Vortex (instead of Splurt/Pyrocuror), he'll just hit his jboots -- or for that matter, any item with an instaclick effect -- and force Shadow Vortex to fall below his buff list. Then he'll simply click the effect back off, leaving a nice open slot for Pyrocuror.</P><P>3) Both debuffs have a 1.5 second casting time, with the usual 2.5 recast delay between them. Crystallized Pumice has a 3 second casting time and can be recasted instantly. All it takes is two quick charges of pumice to take off everything. (Alternatively, two dispels can be memorized and cast in quick succession.)</P><P>4) If the enchanter has 3 or more buff slots, he can simply Pillage himself (removing Siphon Strength, Shadow Vortex, and Pyrocuror all at once).</P><P>5) Unless the enchanter has a level advantage, Nullify Magic works randomly enough that it will often skip Siphon Strength/Shadow Vortex altogether.</P><P>Regardless, it's still far from being a "weak" strategy. I've been using it for around a year now, and very few people are smart enough to do 1) or 3), and only one person I've ever fought -- Faandar -- was smart enough to do 2). So despite its theoretical limitations, it's still a viable tactic.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Oh and another fun tactic...see how well your chanter buddy knows the game by Harmshielding at the beginning of the fight...if he doesn't recognize the spell effect, first thing he's gonna do in all likelihood is tash you...see if he notices.  INVUL people don't generate a resist message.  GL with those nancyboy nukes without tash, chantaman.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Excellent strategy, especially when you and the enchanter begin the fight far away from each other.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Same dot strat will put you all over any druid.  Unlike the mighty Shaman, druid heals suck ass.  You can run him oom pretty easy.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Druids are perhaps the easiest class in the game to use the debuff tactic against. They usually have SoW, so you don't have to worry about the jboots icon getting in the way.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Considering a druid is going to hit me about as often/hard as a level1 rat in west freeport...I really don't see why they'd bother to melee.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>I'd be careful what you assume here. Druids have been known to hit for 100+ in PvP with the right weapons.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>I like how you assume a druid can insta poof the pet or something<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>"Killing" the pet doesn't necessarily mean poofing it. Most of the time, all it takes is two wildfires. Alternatively, the druid might combine his epic effect with his mana-free Snare item to seal the pet's fate. The idea is that once the pet is dead, the druid is free to chase the necro without getting hit.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>...you can dispell your pet just like you can dispell yourself.  You have Arch Lich for mana...druid has PoTG.  If the druid has no brain, dispell any dots out of your first buff slot that he throws on you.  If he magically has a brain, he'll get Winged Death on you sooner or later...best PvP DOT in the game.  That's when you stack Vexing and Bond on him and laugh.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>I personally haven't had a problem annulling Winged Death myself. Also, dots (surprisingly) do their full PvE damage in PvP if they're stacked with a Bond effect. I'm not level 57 yet, but if the spellguides are right, you should actually *lose* a little bit of HP if you try to counter Winged Death with Vexing. (Try this next time you fight a newbie druid: don't annul WD, but instead cast Bond of Death and watch your HP bar. Instead of the expected 100-200, you end up losing nearly 500 HP. You might also want to test this out with your own dots.)</P><P>Cerilius D`Nixx<BR>54 Necromancer, VZ</font></td>
