        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Cerilius</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Take it from a guy who's beaten his fair share of (non tard) 60 Enchanters...(more than a few before I was even 60) once you isolate RuneV and dispell it, or you dot it out of effectiveness, he's going to lose the HP game.  This is long before you're oom from his sieving.</P><P>Enchanters cannot heal themselves, they can only hope to mitigate damage with runes.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>If the enchanter is smart enough to bury Rune V deep within his buffs, and click his instacast items (like jboots, goblin earring, Coldain ring, etc.) after each dispel attempt, then you won't be able to dispel his rune *at all* (not counting sheer luck, where your dispel would skip 10 buffs in a row). As I pointed out in an earlier post, your only hope would be to lifetap through it.</P><P>Over-dotting is also ineffective because enchanters can dispel themselves much faster than you can stack your dots. And if your pet is gone, your dots are getting dispelled, and your lifetaps are being absorbed, what else can you do?</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>They also regen mana half as fast as you, the math works out no matter how you look at it.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Well, let's see. ::pulls out his calculator::</P><P>Clarity II = 11 mana per tick<BR>Lich = 20 mana/-26 HP per tick<BR>Vexing Mordinia = 1098 HP for 495 mana (unnerfed heal in PvP) over 9 ticks</P><P>So, a necro's total mana regen would be (assuming Vexing is used as efficienly as possible) = 20 - 26*495/1098 = 8.27 mana per tick.</P><P>In other words, a necro combining Lich with Vexing Mordinia actually regens LESS mana than an enchanter with Clarity II.</P><P>Of course, this comparison is a little unfair to the necromancer in two ways: first, the enchanter would need to dispel the Vexing effect off himself, costing 50 mana and thus subtracting from his overall mana regen rate (reducing it to approximately 9.81 mana per tick). Second, necros also get Demi Lich at 60 (31 mana/-36 HP), increasing their regen total to 14.77 mana per tick, about 1.5 times that of the enchanter.</P><P>Still, the 5-point difference in mana regeneration rates makes little difference to the outcome of the fight. If you dispel him, he'll protect his buffs by refreshing all his instaclick effects. If you dot him, he'll dispel it. If you lifetap, he'll re-Rune for less mana cost. And after he's done draining all your mana, you become a sitting duck for the weakest of assaults (like charmed pets).</P><P>There's really not much you can do to kill a smart enchanter in a duel.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>If all he did was sieve, he could take 400 mana every 11 seconds.  Consider...I have 3200 mana.  Can you inflict 1800 (high estimate of enchanter's hp + RuneV) damage in 88 seconds (worst case scenario)? I can.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>1800 damage? With what spell, Touch of Night? <img src=icon_smile.gif border=0 align=middle></P><P>As previously mentioned, a well-played enchanter is invulnerable to lifetaps. Also, consider that no good enchanter would just stand there waiting for Mana Sieve to refresh. Instead, he would dodge your spells by backing up out of range, waiting through its 8-second recast time before casting it again. With this strategy, an enchanter can land a sieve on you for each deflux you land on him. If you have 3200 mana, that allows you to deflux the enchanter five times (taking his HP/Rune down to around 800 HP) before running out of mana. Clearly, the necro is at a serious disadvantage in this fight -- and this is if the enchanter DOESN'T recast Rune.</P><P>Cerilius D`Nixx<BR>54 Necromancer, VZ</font></td>
